    category => q{local},
    about => q{Undo commits},
    usage => q{gim uncommit [--force|-f] [-n=i]
},
    help => q{Undo commits.

Allows to undo commits you already made. The changes made by those
commits will then be present in your working directory. The commit
message will be lost (but you may recover it via your shell's
command history).

If you undo more than one commit (via the ‘-n=i’ option with i > 1),
the information what change was in which commit will be lost as
well.

For commits that have not been pushed to any remote yet, this is a
trivial task.

For commits that have already been pushed, an ‘uncommit’ would
require a forced push, as it is rewriting published history. (Check
