$_topic{ simplicity } =
{
    order => 2,
    about => q{How Gim tries to be simpler},
    help => q{Git was written as a power tool for repository
maintainers, then got more options for more diverse workflows,
and unfortunately it never received the reworking and polish it
should have.

For one, Git offers extensive pretty-printing options, yet
by default uses rather unappealing formatting on most of its
commands. There is technical data cluttering the output of
e.g. ‘pull’ or ‘push’, unnecessary verboseness to ‘status’,
and the default output of ‘log’ is dismal.

Gim attempts to prune Git output of unnecessary details, to
format output in a way easily skimmed at a glance, and to make
use of colors to improve legibility.

Some frequently used Git functions hide behind somewhat less
than intuitive combinations of commands and options. Plus,
some features of Git are rather confusing to newcomers, both
without previous VCS knowledge and those coming from e.g.
Subversion or Perforce. One example would be the whole concept
of Staging, which Git documentation also refers to as “the
Index File” in places to confuse you even further.

A side effect of this is that Git documentation, like manual
pages or the built-in help, is lengthy, confusing, and quite
often merely cross-referencing yet other documentation. This
can be quite irritating.

Gim trims down (some would say ruthlessly) on the number of
available options, without compromising too much on functionality.
The commands you will be using dozens of times a day should be
short, easily memorized mnemonics without requiring extra options.

Gim has consciously decided to rename some specific commands
to cater for the more common (and less surprising) use case,
e.g. using ‘revert’ to refer to the reverting of local changes,
not reverting commits by making another commit.

Gim provides documentation for all its commands through ‘gim
help’, and tries to keep things short and to the point, so you
can go back to programming as soon as possible.
}};

$_topic{ safety } =
{
    order => 3,
    about => q{How Gim tries to be safer},
    help => q{There are several features to Git that are, to put
it mildly, flirting with desaster. This is because Git, unlike
many other versioning tools, explicitly allows removing or
overwriting information, even from commits that had been made
long ago. Or get you swamped in the middle of a multi-command
workflow with very few hints on what is going on, or how to
recover from there gracefully.

While some of these features are actually quite useful, the way
Git communicates about those -- or rather, does not communicate
in time -- can be daunting. A good rule of thumb for beginners
is to stay away from any command beginning with ‘re...’, and to
use ‘--force’ only after asking someone more experienced.

Gim tries to be more up-forward with information, especially in
multi-command workflows and potentially damaging operations. As
a rule of thumb, Gim will always ask you before doing anything
